{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15061"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15061"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.17,0.06,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7749"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHypertensive nephropathy is a common cause of chronic kidney disease. Chronic hypertension leads to characteristic changes in renal blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary histological finding in hypertensive nephropathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arteriolar wall thickening with hyaline deposition","Glomerular basement membrane thinning","Tubular epithelial cell hyperplasia","Mesangial cell proliferation","Podocyte foot process effacement"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary histological finding in hypertensive nephropathy is \u003Cstrong\u003Earteriolar wall thickening with hyaline deposition\u003C/strong\u003E. This process, known as hyaline arteriosclerosis, results in narrowing of the vascular lumen and subsequent tissue ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlomerular basement membrane thinning\u003C/strong\u003E is not seen in hypertensive nephropathy - the membrane may actually thicken over time\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETubular epithelial cell hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur - instead, chronic ischaemia leads to tubular atrophy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesangial cell proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a characteristic feature of hypertensive nephropathy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPodocyte foot process effacement\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with conditions causing nephrotic syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vascular changes lead to chronic ischaemia of the kidney tissue, which results in tubular atrophy and interstitial fibrosis as secondary changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hypertensive nephropathy is characterised by hyaline arteriosclerosis with arteriolar wall thickening","Chronic hypertension causes vascular damage leading to tissue ischaemia and subsequent interstitial fibrosis","The key histological feature is hyaline deposition in arteriolar walls causing vessel lumen narrowing"],"references":["In regard to vascular features, narrowing of the vascular lumen may be secondary to hyaline arteriolosclerosisJennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Hart PD, Bakris GL. Hypertensive nephropathy: prevention and treatment recommendations. Expert Opin Pharmacother. 2010 Nov;11(16):2675-86. doi: 10.1517/14656566.2010.485612. Epub 2010 Aug 18. PMID: 20718588."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15061"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:16:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:18:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7749"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul